# Testing Standards

## Test Structure (AAA Pattern)

```typescript
describe('UserService', () => {
  describe('createUser', () => {
    it('should create user with valid data', async () => {
      // Arrange
      const userData = { name: 'John', email: 'john@example.com' };

      // Act
      const user = await userService.createUser(userData);

      // Assert
      expect(user.id).toBeDefined();
      expect(user.name).toBe('John');
    });
  });
});
```

## Naming Conventions

```typescript
// Pattern: should [expected behavior] when [condition]
it('should throw ValidationError when email is missing', () => {});
it('should return null when user not found', () => {});
it('should emit event when order is placed', () => {});
```

## Test Categories

| Type | Purpose | Speed |
|------|---------|-------|
| Unit | Single function/class | Fast |
| Integration | Multiple components | Medium |
| E2E | Full user flow | Slow |

## Mocking

```typescript
// Mock external dependencies
jest.mock('../services/api');

// Use dependency injection for testability
const service = new UserService(mockDatabase, mockLogger);
```

## What to Test

- Happy path (expected behavior)
- Edge cases (empty, null, max values)
- Error conditions (invalid input, failures)
- Boundary conditions (limits, transitions)

## What NOT to Test

- Third-party library internals
- Framework code
- Trivial getters/setters
- Implementation details (test behavior, not code)

## Test Isolation

- Each test should be independent
- Use beforeEach for setup, afterEach for cleanup
- Never depend on test execution order
- Reset mocks between tests
